<!--Naikan--><!--Naikan--><!--Naikan--><!--Naikan--><!--Naikan--><!--Naikan-->

'''Naikan''' (内官)

* '''Naikan''' - In the Japanese {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}}, it refers to {{ill|Kyokan|ja|京官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyokan|qq=}} (capital officials) who are in contrast to {{ill|Gekan|ja|外官|1=Gaikan|lt=Local officials (Gaikan)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gekan|13=User:Immanuelle/Gaikan|qq=}} (provincial officials). These were officials and offices based in the capital.
* '''Naikan''' - Officials serving the imperial court. This term was used for officials working in the {{ill|Imperial Household Ministry|ja|宮内省|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Household Ministry|qq=}} and other offices related to the imperial family under the old system. Known as imperial household officials (宮内官).
* '''Naikan''' - In Chinese, it refers to {{ill|eunuchs|ja|宦官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/eunuchs|qq=}} or female attendants in the imperial court.
* '''Naikan''' - The Japanese translation of the German term *innerer Sinn* (inner sense), also referred to as 内感. It means internal sense, internal sensory perception, or internal awareness. In philosophy, {{ill|Kankan|ja|感官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankan|qq=}} (*Sinn* in German) encompasses both sensory organs and their perceptual functions, considering physiological and psychological functions in a unified manner. While sensory organs related to external perception are called *Gekan* (external sense), the ability to perceive internal consciousness is called *Naikan*. {{ill|Immanuel Kant|ja|イマヌエル・カント|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Immanuel Kant|qq=}} stated, "Time is nothing but the form of inner sense" in contrast to external phenomena related to space such as shape or position (from *Critique of Pure Reason*, A33/B49). Additionally, in the second edition of *Critique of Pure Reason*, particularly in §.24 "On the Application of Categories to the Objects of the Senses in General" (B150-157), he revisits this concept in connection with self-affection (*Affektion* in German).

