* '''Naikan''' - In the Japanese [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]], it refers to {{ill|Kyokan|ja|京官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyokan|qq=}} (capital officials) who are in contrast to {{ill|Gekan|ja|外官|1=Gaikan|lt=Local officials (Gaikan)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gekan|13=User:Immanuelle/Gaikan|qq=}} (provincial officials). These were officials and offices based in the capital. * '''Naikan''' - Officials serving the imperial court. This term was used for officials working in the [[:en:Ministry of the Imperial Household|Imperial Household Ministry]] and other offices related to the imperial family under the old system. Known as imperial household officials (宮内官). * '''Naikan''' - In Chinese, it refers to {{ill|eunuchs|ja|宦官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/eunuchs|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} or female attendants in the imperial court. * '''Naikan''' - The Japanese translation of the German term *innerer Sinn* (inner sense), also referred to as 内感. It means internal sense, internal sensory perception, or internal awareness. In philosophy, {{ill|Kankan|ja|感官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 感覚器}} (*Sinn* in German) encompasses both sensory organs and their perceptual functions, considering physiological and psychological functions in a unified manner. While sensory organs related to external perception are called *Gekan* (external sense), the ability to perceive internal consciousness is called *Naikan*. [[:en:Immanuel Kant|Immanuel Kant]] stated, "Time is nothing but the form of inner sense" in contrast to external phenomena related to space such as shape or position (from *Critique of Pure Reason*, A33/B49). Additionally, in the second edition of *Critique of Pure Reason*, particularly in §.24 "On the Application of Categories to the Objects of the Senses in General" (B150-157), he revisits this concept in connection with self-affection (*Affektion* in German).
